<font color="#FF0000">MTF IS ANGRY, AND JUSTIFIED</font><br>
<tt>Mon Nov  3  5:23:57 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
MTF is angry.<br><br>
He has a right to be angry. The bottom line is that it was<br>
a corrupt political and military system that got us into it, that kept us in it, and that tied everyone's hands so no one could get out of it, until a lot of safe people made tons of money and the Pentagon officer corps got their quota of medals. <br><br>
Furthering these ideas, the fact that elements in Congress fought against the Vietnam Wall Memorial is a testament for that body not wanting to be reminded they had a hand in the sordid affair. The amounts of money poured into constituancies was enormous, and votes for the incumbents was the primary motivation. <br><br>
What was not done in the Vietnam War is as valid a topic as what was done.<br><br>
Between the extremes of motivations, of stopping the spread of communism and of deceit and corruption, lies the truth. We may never know that truth. The effect on those who fought is real, tangible and definable, truth. This society does not now define its warrior class along time honored ways many thousands of years old. The manner in which Vietnam War Veteran's continue to be treated in some sectors is an extension of the abandonment of truth and honesty by those in power then, and now. We were used, used up, and thrown away.<br><br>
There is validity in these points of view. I personally grapple with these issues in my own mind. There is no &quot;right&quot; answer.<br><br>
MTF brings up some real issues with the government, the VA, and not so pretty historical things, that fit right in.  <br><br>
Anger is justified. 
<p><code>-- art16@ix.netcom.com  (Arthur Varanelli) </code><p>


